{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's \"Bilad-e-Islamiya\" from *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Baghdad is evoked as a *gulshan*—an earthly paradise whose every bud (*ghuncha*) itself contains a garden (*chaman*):\n\n> This is that garden whose every bud was a garden in itself;  \n> This is the final tomb of those before whom Rome would tremble.[^1]\n\nHere, the *gulshan* figures an idealized Islamic community: a self-renewing polity of such splendor and might that it made empires quake, rivaling the Koranic Iram of the pillars (mentioned lines prior).[^2]\n\nThe English \"garden\" flattens this layered resonance. In Persian-Urdu poetics, *gulshan* draws from *pairidaeza* (enclosed paradise) as a verdant, symmetrical idyll—chambers of roses, fountains, nightingales—symbolizing cosmic harmony, communal flourishing under divine order, and the soul's ascent amid earthly delights. It connotes not mere horticulture but a perfected society: abundant, enclosed against chaos, fragrant with spiritual vitality, where power blooms organically from piety. \"Garden\" evokes a backyard plot; *gulshan* pulses with the *bāgh* as microcosm of Edenic polity.[^3]",
